# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
GLOBAL = [
    {"hero":True,"sub":"Conflicts & Security","h3":"Iran halts US talks as Strait of Hormuz stays shut","summary":"Tehran paused negotiations with Washington after fresh strikes, leaving the vital oil chokepoint effectively closed and tanker traffic near zero.","body":["Iran announced a pause to peace talks with the United States after renewed tit-for-tat strikes, and warned it would keep the Strait of Hormuz blocked until Israel halts operations in Lebanon and Gaza. Tehran framed continued Israeli strikes in southern Lebanon as a violation of the June memorandum of understanding meant to wind down the wider conflict within 60 days.","Traffic through Hormuz collapsed to a fraction of pre-war levels with almost no tanker transits, even as a US Navy-overseen maritime center widened a route near Oman to reassert passage. Delegations from both sides reportedly traveled to Qatar, but Iran said no substantive meetings were scheduled in the coming days, keeping global oil and shipping markets on edge."],"sources":[("CBS News","https://www.cbsnews.com/live-updates/us-iran-war-israel-hezbollah-strait-of-hormuz-peace-deal-talks/"),("RFE/RL","https://www.rferl.org/a/iran-war-us-hormuz-oil-blockade-gulf-israel/33640284.html")]},
    {"sub":"Conflicts & Security","h3":"Israel renews strikes in southern Lebanon despite framework deal","summary":"Israeli forces hit several targets in southern Lebanon just days after signing a framework agreement aimed at ending decades of conflict.","body":["Israel carried out fresh strikes in southern Lebanon, two days after it signed a framework agreement with Beirut intended to end a long-running conflict. Lebanon's state news agency reported several impacts, and Iran cited the strikes as grounds to keep the Strait of Hormuz closed.","The renewed fire underscored how fragile the wider regional ceasefire architecture remains. A 14-point memorandum signed earlier in the month had stipulated the war would end on all fronts including Lebanon, with the US and Iran pledging to protect Lebanese sovereignty, commitments now openly in doubt."],"sources":[("CBS News","https://www.cbsnews.com/live-updates/us-iran-war-israel-hezbollah-strait-of-hormuz-peace-deal-talks/"),("Times of Israel","https://www.timesofisrael.com/liveblog-june-29-2026/")]},
    {"sub":"Conflicts & Security","h3":"Putin rejects Kyiv push to limit long-range strikes","summary":"The Russian leader said Moscow will press on with the war and dismissed Ukraine's offer of a mutual halt to long-range missile attacks.","body":["President Vladimir Putin said Russia would continue its war on Ukraine and rejected Kyiv's proposal for a mutual stop to long-range strikes. In a state television interview he argued Ukraine floated the idea because its forces were under pressure along the front, claiming Russian deep strikes were more destructive.","President Volodymyr Zelenskyy countered that Ukraine would keep up operations that weaken Russia's ability to fight. Kyiv has been hitting Russian energy sites with long-range drones, including refineries in Krasnodar and facilities in occupied Crimea, part of a sustained campaign against Moscow's war economy."],"sources":[("Al Jazeera","https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/6/29/russia-ukraine-war-why-has-putin-rejected-limits-on-long-range-strikes"),("NPR","https://www.npr.org/2026/06/26/nx-s1-5872256/russia-ukraine-war-drone-strikes")]},
    {"sub":"Conflicts & Security","h3":"Ukrainian drones spark fire at Russian Black Sea refinery","summary":"A drone barrage triggered a blaze at a refinery in Krasnodar, with one person killed and homes damaged by falling debris.","body":["A fire broke out at an oil refinery in Slavyansk-na-Kubani in Russia's Krasnodar region after one of Ukraine's heaviest drone bombardments. Several houses were damaged by debris and at least one person was killed.","The attacks extended Kyiv's campaign against Russian energy infrastructure, with strikes also reported on facilities in Kerch in occupied Crimea and Port Kavkaz. Ukraine says the operations cut the resources fueling Russia's military, while Moscow responded with its own strikes on Ukrainian territory."],"sources":[("NPR","https://www.npr.org/2026/06/26/nx-s1-5872256/russia-ukraine-war-drone-strikes"),("Al Jazeera","https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/6/25/as-ukraine-seizes-first-chance-to-win-war-horrors-come-home-to-russia")]},
    {"sub":"Conflicts & Security","h3":"Oil output slumps as Hormuz shutdown bites","summary":"US energy data showed Middle Eastern producers cutting output by more than 11 million barrels a day as the strait closure choked exports.","body":["The closure of the Strait of Hormuz forced Middle Eastern oil producers to slash output by more than 11 million barrels per day, according to US Energy Information Administration figures cited in coverage of the crisis. The disruption rerouted shipping away from the strait and the Red Sea.","The supply shock rippled through global travel and trade, halting many flights into the region and lifting freight and insurance costs. A US Navy-overseen information center widened a route near Oman to allow naval traffic in both directions, signaling a challenge to Iran's grip on the waterway."],"sources":[("Wikipedia","https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2026_Strait_of_Hormuz_crisis"),("Britannica","https://www.britannica.com/event/2026-Iran-war")]},
    {"sub":"Diplomacy & Trade","h3":"Erdogan demands seat in Europe's defense plans before summit","summary":"Turkey's president said Ankara must be included in all European security structures, a week ahead of hosting the NATO summit.","body":["President Recep Tayyip Erdogan said Turkey must be part of every European defense and security structure, speaking days before Ankara hosts the NATO summit. He pressed for access to the EU's 150-billion-euro Security Action for Europe initiative as the continent rearms against Russia and braces for a possible US pullback.","Erdogan is expected to use the gathering to showcase Turkey's strategic weight and seek concessions from Washington, including the sale of jet engines worth hundreds of millions of dollars. NATO chief Mark Rutte said the summit would underline the alliance's readiness to defend every inch of its territory."],"sources":[("Al Arabiya","https://english.alarabiya.net/News/world/2026/06/29/turkey-must-be-included-in-european-security-structures-erdogan-ahead-of-nato-summit"),("Turkish Minute","https://turkishminute.com/2026/06/29/erdogan-says-turkey-must-be-included-in-european-defense-plans-ahead-of-nato-summit/")]},
    {"sub":"Diplomacy & Trade","h3":"NATO heads to Ankara with bigger budgets on the agenda","summary":"Defense spending tops the agenda as alliance leaders prepare to meet in Turkey on July 7 and 8.","body":["NATO leaders are set to gather in Ankara on July 7 and 8 with higher defense spending as the central theme, following last year's pledge to invest 5% of GDP in defense by 2035. The alliance's deputy commander has pushed for the summit to spur greater outlays and project unity.","Secretary General Mark Rutte said the meeting would demonstrate Europe's commitment to a stronger military amid Russian pressure and uncertainty over the US role. Host Turkey is positioning itself as a pivotal player in the continent's security buildout."],"sources":[("Washington Times","https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2026/jun/25/bigger-defense-spending-top-agenda-upcoming-nato-summit-turkey/"),("Foreign Policy","https://foreignpolicy.com/2026/06/29/nato-trump-erdogan-ankara-summit-europe-defense-russia/")]},
    {"sub":"Diplomacy & Trade","h3":"Herzog courts EU backing for Israel-Lebanon deal in Bucharest","summary":"Israel's president urged European states to support the new Israel-Lebanon framework during a state visit to Romania.","body":["President Isaac Herzog met Romanian counterpart Nicusor Dan in Bucharest, where the two discussed cooperation on technology, cyber, artificial intelligence, security, agriculture and tourism. Herzog praised the recently signed Israel-Lebanon framework and called on EU members to get behind it.","The visit reflected Israel's push to rally European support for the fragile regional agreements even as renewed strikes in Lebanon and Iran's pause on talks cast doubt over the broader peace effort."],"sources":[("Times of Israel","https://www.timesofisrael.com/liveblog-june-29-2026/")]},
    {"sub":"Diplomacy & Trade","h3":"US and China sketch a managed trade truce","summary":"Washington and Beijing outlined a framework for managed trade, tariff rollbacks and Chinese purchases of US goods to steady relations.","body":["US and Chinese leaders signaled a push for what they called a constructive relationship of strategic stability, built around a managed trade approach. The plan envisions a board of trade for non-sensitive goods, selective cuts to tariff and non-tariff barriers and Chinese commitments to buy US aircraft and address critical mineral concerns.","Analysts cautioned that durable peace remains elusive, with the two sides defining reciprocity very differently. The US trade representative extended tariff exclusions on 178 Chinese products into November, following pledges from an earlier agreement."],"sources":[("World Economic Forum","https://www.weforum.org/stories/2026/06/china-trade-policy-us-relations/"),("China Briefing","https://www.china-briefing.com/news/us-china-relations-in-the-trump-2-0-implications/")]},
    {"sub":"Diplomacy & Trade","h3":"EU disburses first slice of Ukraine support loan","summary":"Brussels released 3.2 billion euros under its Ukraine loan after a June summit reaffirmed long-term backing for Kyiv.","body":["The EU made the first disbursement of 3.2 billion euros under its Ukraine support loan on June 25, following a Brussels summit where leaders reaffirmed their commitment to Kyiv's defense. They called for faster delivery of air defenses, ammunition, drones and missiles.","Leaders also welcomed progress on Ukraine's accession path, including a second accession conference and the opening of the fundamentals cluster. The summit adopted conclusions spanning the long-term EU budget, competitiveness, migration and enlargement."],"sources":[("European Council","https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/meetings/european-council/2026/06/18-19/"),("European Commission","https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_26_90")]},
    {"sub":"Diplomacy & Trade","h3":"Asia-Pacific security ties deepen around AI and drills","summary":"Regional partners broadened cooperation into artificial intelligence and maritime exercises as security links tightened.","body":["Talks among Asia-Pacific partners expanded into artificial intelligence and joint maritime drills as governments worked to deepen security ties. The moves came against a backdrop of heightened tension over trade and contested waters.","The push reflected a broader trend of middle powers hedging amid uncertainty over the US security role and an assertive China, with technology cooperation increasingly woven into traditional defense planning."],"sources":[("Nikkei Asia","https://asia.nikkei.com/politics/international-relations")]},
    {"sub":"Humanitarian & Climate","h3":"Europe heatwave death toll passes 1,300, WHO says","summary":"The World Health Organization reported more than 1,300 excess deaths across Europe since June 21 as a brutal heatwave gripped the continent.","body":["The WHO said more than 1,300 excess deaths linked to extreme heat had been recorded across Europe since June 21. France logged around 1,000 more deaths than expected and Spain recorded over 400 that may be heat-related, with hospitals and emergency services overwhelmed.","Records tumbled across the continent, with the UK posting its hottest June day and France marking its warmest day since measurements began in 1947. Temperatures topped 40C in Spain and Germany, straining power grids and prompting health alerts for tens of millions."],"sources":[("Euronews","https://www.euronews.com/my-europe/2026/06/28/france-sees-around-1000-excess-deaths-during-brutal-heatwave"),("Al Jazeera","https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/6/29/more-than-1300-deaths-in-europe-amid-heatwave-what-can-countries-do")]},
    {"sub":"Humanitarian & Climate","h3":"Guterres demands action and presses AI firms on data centers","summary":"The UN chief urged bolder climate action as the heatwave raged, telling AI companies to come clean on their energy and water use.","body":["UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres issued an impassioned appeal for more ambitious global climate action to prevent irreversible damage, delivering a keynote at London Climate Action Week as the heatwave gripped Europe. He laid out a blueprint for accelerating the clean energy transition.","Guterres also called on AI firms to come clean about the full environmental footprint of their data centers, citing carbon, water and land impacts. He urged developed nations to honor pledges to double, then triple, adaptation finance before shocks turn into catastrophes."],"sources":[("UN News","https://news.un.org/en/story/2026/06/1167785"),("GlobalSecurity","https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/news/2026/06/mil-260623-unnews05.htm")]},
    {"sub":"Humanitarian & Climate","h3":"Sudan endures third year of famine as kitchens shut","summary":"Around 25 million people face acute hunger in Sudan, with famine confirmed and aid funding collapsing.","body":["Sudan entered a third consecutive year of famine with about 25 million people, half the population, facing acute hunger and famine confirmed in several areas. More than 40% of community kitchens, a lifeline for the displaced, have closed in six months as funding dried up.","The World Food Programme said it needs around 600 million dollars over six months to scale up support and push back the threat of famine spreading. Sudan received nothing from a revamped US food aid program, deepening the shortfall in one of the world's worst hunger crises."],"sources":[("Council on Foreign Relations","https://www.cfr.org/articles/trumps-revamped-food-for-peace-bypasses-the-countries-closest-to-famine"),("World Food Programme","https://www.wfp.org/stories/funding-cuts-six-critical-wfp-operations-risk")]},
    {"sub":"Humanitarian & Climate","h3":"DR Congo hunger hits record 28 million amid funding cuts","summary":"One in four people in DR Congo are food insecure as conflict and aid shortfalls push millions toward emergency hunger levels.","body":["A record 28 million people in the Democratic Republic of Congo, roughly one in four, are food insecure, including 10.3 million in the conflict-hit east. Nearly 4 million face emergency hunger, just one step below famine, according to food security assessments.","Aid cuts have made the crisis worse, with only a fifth of the UN response plan funded and essential services shutting for millions. The 2025 global humanitarian appeal drew just 12 billion dollars, the lowest in a decade, leaving 25 million fewer people reached than the year before."],"sources":[("OCHA","https://www.unocha.org/news/todays-top-news-global-humanitarian-overview-2026-sudan-occupied-palestinian-territory"),("Concern","https://concernusa.org/news/democratic-republic-congo-crisis-explained/")]},
    {"sub":"Humanitarian & Climate","h3":"Gaza ceasefire holds in name as civilians stay in limbo","summary":"A ceasefire is nominally in place in Gaza but the population remains crowded into a fraction of the territory amid widespread ruin.","body":["A ceasefire in Gaza is holding at least in name, but the surviving population remains crowded into less than half the territory, much of it reduced to rubble. Aid groups warn that conditions on the ground remain dire despite the formal pause.","Humanitarians say access and funding shortfalls continue to hamper relief, with Gaza among the territories flagged in the UN's global humanitarian overview for 2026 alongside Sudan, Ukraine and DR Congo."],"sources":[("International Crisis Group","https://www.crisisgroup.org/cmt/global/10-conflicts-watch-2026"),("OCHA","https://www.unocha.org/news/todays-top-news-occupied-palestinian-territory-syria-sudan-ukraine-myanmar")]},
    {"sub":"Humanitarian & Climate","h3":"WHO and governments weigh defenses against killer heat","summary":"As Europe's death toll mounted, officials debated how countries can better protect people from increasingly deadly heatwaves.","body":["With more than 1,300 heat-related deaths recorded, health authorities and governments turned to the question of how to shield populations from worsening heatwaves. Measures under discussion include early warning systems, cooling centers and reforms to housing and urban planning.","Experts stress that contingency systems must be in place before shocks escalate into humanitarian and economic disasters, echoing UN calls for far stronger investment in climate adaptation across vulnerable regions and aging European cities alike."],"sources":[("Al Jazeera","https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/6/29/more-than-1300-deaths-in-europe-amid-heatwave-what-can-countries-do"),("Time","https://time.com/article/2026/06/23/heatwave-europe-record-high-temperatures-deadly-extreme-heat-stress-safety/")]},
    {"sub":"Humanitarian & Climate","h3":"Myanmar junta regains ground as China backs the generals","summary":"Myanmar's military has clawed back the initiative in the civil war, helped by decisive support from China.","body":["Myanmar's ruling military has regained the upper hand in the civil war after a period when rebels looked ascendant, analysts say. China has thrown its weight decisively behind the junta, shaping the conflict's trajectory.","Other Asian powers appear to be betting that military control will endure even after a planned vote installs a nominally civilian government, leaving displaced communities and humanitarian needs to mount with little international attention."],"sources":[("International Crisis Group","https://www.crisisgroup.org/cmt/global/10-conflicts-watch-2026"),("Middle East Eye","https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/israel-palestine-syria-yemen-and-sudan-among-conflicts-watch-2026-report-says")]},
]

NETHERLANDS = [
    {"hero":True,"sub":"Politics & Policy","h3":"Defense plan bets big on unmanned weapons systems","summary":"The Jetten cabinet unveiled a new defense strategy aiming for more than half of military capability to come from unmanned systems within five years.","body":["Defense Minister Dilan Yesilgoz and State Secretary Boswijk presented a new defense note titled Samen Voorwaarts, setting a goal for over half of operational capabilities to rely on unmanned weapons systems within five years. The plan reframes Dutch defense for what officials called a world ruled by the strongest.","The shift comes as the Netherlands prepares for the NATO summit in Ankara, where higher defense spending dominates the agenda. Critics noted the ministry is asking more of Dutch society while becoming less transparent about how the money is being spent."],"sources":[("NOS","https://nos.nl/artikel/2620786-defensie-zet-in-op-onbemenste-wapensystemen-in-recht-van-de-sterkste-wereld")]},
    {"sub":"Politics & Policy","h3":"Corona inquiry enters fifth week of hearings","summary":"The parliamentary committee investigating the pandemic response held its fifth round of hearings in The Hague.","body":["The parliamentary Corona inquiry commission opened its fifth hearing week, running from Monday June 29 through Friday. The sessions continue the scrutiny of decisions taken during the pandemic and their consequences for public health and society.","The inquiry forms part of a broader reckoning over how the Netherlands managed the crisis, with testimony feeding into recommendations for handling future emergencies."],"sources":[("Tweede Kamer","https://www.tweedekamer.nl/debat_en_vergadering")]},
    {"sub":"Politics & Policy","h3":"Cabinet earmarks 250 million euros to cut nitrogen","summary":"The Jetten government set out a package to halve nitrogen emissions by 2035, a long-running flashpoint in Dutch politics.","body":["The minority cabinet of D66, VVD and CDA presented a 250-million-euro package aimed at cutting nitrogen emissions by 50% by 2035. Nitrogen has been one of the most contentious issues in Dutch politics, stalling construction and straining relations with farmers.","As a minority government the cabinet must still assemble parliamentary majorities for its plans, making the package an early test of its ability to build support across the opposition on a deeply divisive file."],"sources":[("DutchReview","https://dutchreview.com/news/new-dutch-cabinet-unveils-coalition-plans/"),("NL Times","https://nltimes.nl/categories/politics")]},
    {"sub":"Politics & Policy","h3":"Rotterdam unveils 5.1 billion euro coalition program","summary":"Rotterdam's new city coalition set out a multibillion-euro plan centered on housing, mobility and growth.","body":["Rotterdam presented a coalition program worth 5.1 billion euros, focused on housing, mobility and economic growth. The plan signals ambitious local investment as the country's second-largest city wrestles with housing shortages and infrastructure pressure.","The package lands amid national debate over how to accelerate homebuilding while meeting climate and nitrogen targets, with cities increasingly setting their own course on development."],"sources":[("NL Times","https://nltimes.nl/categories/politics"),("ING THINK","https://think.ing.com/articles/dutch-parties-reach-minority-coalition-agreement/")]},
    {"sub":"Economy & Housing","h3":"House price growth cools toward 5 percent","summary":"Dutch home prices rose around 5 percent year on year as investor sales of former rentals eased pressure on the owner market.","body":["The Dutch house price index slowed to roughly 5% year on year in early 2026, down from a sharper climb in 2025, with the average home now near 486,000 euros. That equates to roughly 20,000 to 25,000 euros more than a year earlier on a typical property.","Analysts linked the moderation to investors selling former rental homes, which expanded supply for owner-occupiers. Rabobank still expects increases near 5% for the year, while ABN AMRO forecasts a slower rise closer to 3%."],"sources":[("Global Property Guide","https://www.globalpropertyguide.com/europe/netherlands/price-history"),("Rabobank","https://www.rabobank.com/knowledge/d011508452-dutch-housing-market-quarterly-no-signs-of-cooling-even-as-supply-grows")]},
    {"sub":"Economy & Housing","h3":"IMF trims Dutch growth outlook to 1.2 percent","summary":"The Dutch economy is projected to slow this year as global uncertainty and domestic bottlenecks weigh on activity.","body":["After resilient 1.9% real GDP growth in 2025, the IMF projects Dutch economic growth slowing to 1.2% in 2026. Elevated global uncertainty and domestic structural bottlenecks are dampening consumption, investment and trade.","The cooler outlook arrives as the country faces pressure on housing, energy and labor, with the minority cabinet trying to push through investment plans against a tighter fiscal and political backdrop."],"sources":[("Global Property Guide","https://www.globalpropertyguide.com/europe/netherlands/price-history")]},
    {"sub":"Economy & Housing","h3":"Netherlands set for EU's highest air passenger tax","summary":"The country is on course to introduce the highest air passenger levy in the European Union, with charges expected to top 40 euros a ticket.","body":["The Netherlands is poised to bring in the EU's highest air passenger tax, with levies expected to exceed 40 euros per ticket. The move ties into broader efforts to curb aviation emissions and manage growth at Schiphol.","The aviation sector is meanwhile pushing greener fuel, with construction underway on the country's first sustainable aviation fuel plant as KLM targets a 14% blending goal by 2030. The tax has drawn pushback from carriers worried about competitiveness."],"sources":[("DutchNews.nl","https://www.dutchnews.nl/category/schiphol-2/"),("KLM","https://news.klm.com/made-possible-by-klm-construction-begins-on-the-netherlands-first-saf-factory/")]},
    {"sub":"Economy & Housing","h3":"Free-sector rents seen rising up to 7 percent","summary":"Private rental costs are projected to climb between 4 and 7 percent this year while regulated rents stay capped.","body":["Free-sector rents in the Netherlands are projected to grow between 4% and 7% over 2026, while regulated rents rise more modestly under legal caps. The split underscores persistent strain in a tight rental market.","With home prices still climbing and supply constrained, renters face continued affordability pressure even as investor sales add some owner-occupied stock. Housing remains a central concern for the new cabinet and big cities alike."],"sources":[("Investropa","https://investropa.com/blogs/news/netherlands-rents"),("Rabobank","https://www.rabobank.com/knowledge/dutch-housing-market")]},
    {"sub":"Society & Culture","h3":"Hottest June day ever recorded in the Netherlands","summary":"Ell in Limburg hit 39.4C, smashing a national June record that had stood since 1947 as code red blanketed much of the country.","body":["The village of Ell in Midden-Limburg reached 39.4C, setting a new Dutch record for June and beating the 37.9C measured in Venlo back in 1947. Code red warnings covered a large part of the country on Friday June 26 during an exceptional heat episode.","It was also the first month the KNMI used its new heat-strength index, a 0 to 10 scale combining temperature, humidity, wind and solar radiation to capture how heat actually feels. Large areas endured tropical nights with temperatures staying above 20C."],"sources":[("Weeronline","https://www.weeronline.nl/nieuws/26-6-2026-hoogste-juni-temperatuur-ooit-gemeten"),("KNMI","https://www.knmi.nl/over-het-knmi/nieuws/liveblog-hitte-vanaf-22-juni-2026")]},
    {"sub":"Society & Culture","h3":"Almere stabbing leaves three injured, three arrested","summary":"Three people were hurt, two seriously, in a stabbing in Almere, with three suspects detained.","body":["Three people were injured, two of them seriously, in a stabbing in Almere on June 28, and three suspects were arrested. The incident added to a string of violent episodes in the city.","Almere Buiten-Hout also saw two consecutive nights of armed scooter thefts around the same period, raising local concern over public safety in the Flevoland city."],"sources":[("NL Times","https://nltimes.nl/categories/crime")]},
    {"sub":"Society & Culture","h3":"Storm damage claims surge after stormy weekend","summary":"Insurers reported a jump in claims after a weekend of severe weather swept across the Netherlands.","body":["Storm damage claims surged following a weekend of severe weather across the country, with the swing from extreme heat to thunderstorms typical of an unsettled late-June pattern. Households and businesses reported damage from wind and downpours.","The turbulent conditions capped a dramatic stretch of weather that began with record heat and code red warnings before breaking into storms, leaving emergency services and insurers busy."],"sources":[("NL Times","https://nltimes.nl/")]},
    {"sub":"Society & Culture","h3":"Two drown in separate water incidents during heat","summary":"A man died in Vught and another in a paddleboarding accident in Haren as warm weather drew people to the water.","body":["A 35-year-old man drowned in Vught and another died in a paddleboarding accident in Haren on June 29, as the heat pushed many Dutch residents toward lakes and waterways. The deaths underscored the seasonal spike in water-related accidents.","Safety officials regularly warn that cold water and crowded swimming spots raise risks during heatwaves, when demand to cool off surges across the country's rivers, lakes and canals."],"sources":[("NL Times","https://nltimes.nl/")]},
]

MOOD = {"h3":"Sfeer vandaag","p":"Na een uitzonderlijke hittegolf met code rood en het warmste juni-record ooit in Ell ademt het land voorzichtig uit. Stevige onweersbuien hebben de drukkende lucht doorbroken en zorgden voor schade en wateroverlast in een groot deel van Nederland. De stemming is gemengd, opluchting dat de tropische nachten voorbij zijn, maar ook zorg over het klimaat en over de twee verdrinkingen tijdens de hitte. In Den Haag domineren defensie, stikstof en de wooncrisis het gesprek, terwijl veel mensen vooral hopen op een rustiger en koeler einde van de maand."}
